post_text:
The Jr/Sr High and Elementary Schools will be offering evening hours next Monday from 7:00 PM to 8:00 PM at the Jr/Sr High School. Mandy Mutschler and Becky Edwards will both be posted at the main entrance to the Jr/Sr High School. These evening hours will allow parents who cannot visit the school during typical office hours to do the following:
> Drop off any completed forms from Smart Start
> Collect Smart Start packets if they were unable to attend
> Drop off any textbooks that were not returned at the end of the 2019-20 school year
> Pick up any materials that teachers may have ready for online students for this fall (teachers will notify students if materials are ready)

We hope that this is a helpful service and appreciate your flexibility as we start this unique school year!

post_text:
Good Morning,

On August 19th, we will be conducting Smart Start from 9:00 Am to 5:00 PM. This event will be held outdoors in front of the JSH in a drive-up fashion similar to our lunch and textbook pick-up.

Since we have been unable to get the 7th grade as a whole into our building, Mr. Leader and Mrs. Serne will be conducting nine-student tours of the building throughout the day. In order to sign up for your 7th-grade student for a tour, please click on the link below. Tours will take less than 30 minutes. Parents will not be allowed to join the tours to ensure our numbers stay below the currently allowed number.

Sign-up link: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/10c084ba4a62aa0fd0-7thgrade

If you have any questions, feel free to contact Mr. Leader, Mrs. Serne or the JSH Office.

We look forward to seeing you all on August 19th.

Have a great day!

JSH Administration

post_text: On behalf of Saranac Community Schools and the Class of 2020, we want to extend a HUGE "Thank You" to our families, community, and staff for participating in the Class of 2020 parade salute. It warmed our hearts to have nearly 300 vehicles parade through and congratulate our seniors. A special thanks to the decorating group who made the grounds so "2020" festive, the senior parent group for your organization, the Ionia Co. sheriff's Dept, the Saranac Fire Dept., and the many other who contributed. Again, Thank you for making this so special to a wonderful group of young men and women.

post_text: As many of you know Sunday, May 31, 2020 would have been graduation for the Saranac High School Class of 2020. With school closed, we have found a way to safely honor the graduates. The graduating Class of 2020 will be lined up along Otto Laabs Ln in the back of the high school and up to the football field. You are welcome to drive by and give a congratulatory wave. If you would like to be a part of the start of the parade meet in front of the high school at 6:45pm with a departure time of 7pm. Please stay in your cars and follow the escort led by the Ionia County Sherriff's Department and the Saranac Fire Department to where the seniors will be socially distanced waiting for you to drive by. The football field lights will be lit in their honor for 58 minutes, representing the 58 graduates. Let's give these kids a big salute on what should have been a fun-filled memorable day, with never before made memories for a graduating class.

post_text:
6th Grade Students And Parents:

I hope that you are all doing well. I am excited to welcome you to the JSH this Fall! Typically, we would be getting together right now with you for 7th-grade Orientation NIght. I would also have visited the 6th-grade classrooms by now and we would usually host the 6th graders for a morning of activities and lunch at the JSH in late May/early June. Since these are no longer options, It is my hope to do the following:

1. I hope to set up a virtual orientation meeting via Zoom later in May. I will work with the elementary school to collect parent and student emails. The invitation will be sent via email.
2. It is our plan to schedule an in-person open house/building tour in late July or early August, allowing students and parents to explore the building.
3. The JSH will also host Smart Start in mid-August for all JSH students. More details are forthcoming.

I hope that you are all staying safe, and I am excited to see you soon!

Joshua Leader

post_text:
I case you have not already heard, Hope Helminski, our Junior Achievement Student Ambassador from Saranac, has been selected to address a panel and represent teens across America!

“CNBC and Junior Achievement Host Virtual Town Hall for Teens on COVID-19 On April 23 from 1 pm to 2 pm ET, Junior Achievement (JA) and CNBC will be holding a Virtual Town Hall. The JA + CNBC Virtual Town Hall will address teens’ questions and concerns related to the financial impact of COVID-19. This is being made available to students, teachers, and parents seeking answers to questions like, “Why are people losing jobs?” “How will this impact my plans for college?” and “Are we going to be okay?”

To answer teens’ questions, CNBC has assembled a panel of experts in the areas of economics, financial planning, financial wellness, and education. The panel’s moderator is CNBC Senior Personal Finance Correspondent Sharon Epperson.”

post_text:
The Saranac Honor Society inducted 8 members into its ranks on April 14, 2020. Due to Covid 19, the official induction ceremony needed to be postponed. To accommodate the school closure and also honor the inductees, a zoom meeting was held to allow the inductees to say the National Honor Society Pledge. When the social distancing order is lifted, the Honor Society will host a formal ceremony to honor these members and perform the last pieces of the induction. Congratulations to the new inductees Cora Bangert, Calista Chadwick, Megan Chipman, Paigelyn Guernsey, Camryn Jackson, Natalie Olsen, Breanna Sterzick and Logan Wood.

Pictured saying the NHS pledge:
top row: Logan Wood, Nancy Helminski (Adviser), Hope Helminski (current member), Logan Gillette (president)

second row: Paigelyn Guernsey, Breanna Sterzick, Grayson Rasmus (current member)

third row: Natalie Olsen, Cora Bangert, Camryn Jackson

fourth row: Megan Chipman, Calista Chadwick, Kiarra Lambert (current member)

post_text:
The Saranac FFA hosted a science fair for middle school students at Saranac Jr/Sr High on January 16,
2020. Students had six weeks to design, perform and analyze an experiment about a topic in Agriculture
and Natural Resources. A sample of the topics included water loss in eggs, color vs taste of maple syrup
and light type on plant growth. Students were judged on their scientific report, poster display and
presentation skills. Principal Mr. Leader and former Palo principal, Mrs. Reams, judged their
presentations while classroom teacher, Mrs. Young, evaluated their reports and posters. Winning
individuals and teams received cash prizes sponsored by Dr. Thaddeus Williams, a former Saranac FFA
member. The winners, pictured below, are from left to right.
Grace Chase - first individual, Abigail Janson - second individual, Marisa Klahn and Alison Thompson -
first team, Dylon Bollone and Harrison VanKuiken - second team.

Saranac Elementary School
October 28, 2019 at 11:18 AM ·

Good Morning Staff and Parents,

As of right now, the Remind App used by SCS for snow-day notification is no longer functioning for our district. We have exceeded the number of clients allowable on the free app. Moving to a subscription is quite costly with this program, so we are exploring a number of options for emergency notification.

Given that winter weather is fast approaching, we are looking to have a plan in place for communication as soon as possible. Until this plan is in place, we recommend that parents and students take advantage of the notification services available through local media outlets (WOODTV8, FOX17, WZZM).

We will continue to use the options available to us to communicate with parents (Facebook, Twitter, and parent email groups).

As soon as we have more information, it will be forwarded to staff, parents and students.

Thank you for your patience. Have a great day!

post_text:
Parents and Community Members,

Saranac Community Schools remains committed to the safety of our students, staff, community, and environment. In saying that, I would like to share a quick update in regard to recent events as they relate to Eastern Equine Encephalitis, which is transmitted by mosquitoes.

The school district is currently consulting with our pest management company to explore options to ensure the safety of all. If necessary, the district will post any applications of pesticides as we have done in the past.

In the meantime, if you are attending an activity, meeting, or other events on school grounds, particularly at dusk, we ask you to consider the following:
* applying insect repellent
* wearing long pants
* wearing long sleeve shirts

Again the safety of our students, staff, community members, and environment are of utmost importance. We appreciate your continued support and understanding

Good Afternoon Parents,

As part of our efforts to provide appropriate crisis response for our staff and students, SCS administration has made arrangements for the organization, HOPE: Animal-Assisted Crisis Response Teams, to have a number of canine response teams in the JSH and elementary buildings Tuesday and Wednesday.

The canine teams will work in coordination with the counselors we have arranged to be on-site assisting students in coping with the grieving process. The elementary canine team will work specifically with the sixth grade staff and students, providing assistance in that wing of the building.

I have attached a link to video provided by the organization outlining their work. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact any district administrator.

Thank you for your support throughout this difficult process.

HOPE Animal -Assisted Crisis Response

post_text:
What an amazing few days of moving and prepping the newly renovated high school. The teaching and support staff have been amazing with help from community members and the Saranac Fire Department.

We also had hours of help from Doug Abel, Mark Talcott and Danny Barnick. The cheer squad, volleyball players, football players, and a number of parents and students helped the cause over the course of the last few days. Please thank any of these people and/or groups when you see them.

post_text:
The Better Together for Saranac (BT4S) group with some wonderful sponsors provided backpacks and supplies for Saranac Elementary students. The supporting sponsors were Bruce and Margaret Chadwick, Alvin and Anne Smith, Luke Brogger/Quality Hardwoods, Chrouch Communications, Fountain Fundraising, Saranac Community Association, Saranac Elementary PTSO, St. Anthony's Catholic Church, and the many folks who dropped off donations for the event.
Thank you, Community of Saranac

post_text: What a great night at the Saranac Elementary Open House. Special thanks to the Better Together for Saranac (BT4S) group, J Austin Farms, Michigan State Police, Ionia County Sheriff's Department, and the Saranac Fire Department. Of course a HUGE shout out to the wonderful staff of Saranac Community Schools.
